China Stocks: Minsheng Banking, Shenhua Energy, Yanzhou Coal

-- B y   B l o o m b e r g   N e w s
-- 
2011-03-28T07:49:32Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-03-27/china-construction-bank-dongfeng-huaxia-china-equity-preview.html
Shares of the following companies
had unusual moves in  China  trading. Stock symbols are in
parentheses as of 3 p.m. close.  The Shanghai Composite Index, which tracks the bigger of
China’s stock exchanges, rose 6.19, or 0.2 percent, to 2,984.01.
The  CSI 300 Index (SHSZ300)  slipped 0.1 percent to 3,290.57.  China Minsheng Banking Corp. (600016 CH), the nation’s
first privately owned bank, gained 2.6 percent to 5.51 yuan, the
most since Nov. 3. The lender said net income for 2010 rose 45
percent from a year earlier to 17.6 billion yuan ($2.68
billion).  China Pacific Insurance (Group) Co. (601601 CH), the
nation’s third-biggest insurer, added 1 percent to 22.49 yuan
after saying profit rose 16 percent to 8.56 billion yuan last
year as premiums expanded. That compared with the 7.85 billion
yuan median estimate of 10 analysts surveyed by Bloomberg News.  China Shenhua Energy Co. (601088 CH), the nation’s largest
coal producer, added 1.4 percent to 29.59 yuan after the company
said net income for 2010 rose to 38.1 billion yuan last year on
increasing prices of the fuel.  Western Mining Co. (601168 CH), China’s fourth-largest
maker of zinc concentrate, advanced 1.9 percent to 18.38 yuan
after saying net income for 2010 increased 64 percent in 2010 to
989.4 million yuan.  Xinjiang Goldwind Science & Technology Co. (002202 CH), the
country’s second-biggest maker of  wind turbines , slid 1 percent
to 21.11 yuan. Net income for 2010 rose 31 percent from a year
earlier to 2.29 billion yuan, the company said. That compares
with a mean estimate for profit of 2.44 billion yuan from a
Bloomberg survey of 11 analysts.  Yanzhou Coal Mining Co. (600188 CH), China’s fourth-biggest
coal miner, jumped 5.3 percent to 34.94 yuan, a record-high. The
company said full-year net income more than doubled to 9.3
billion yuan in 2010.  --Zhang Shidong. Editor: Allen Wan  To contact Bloomberg News staff for this story:
